#!/bin/bash
echo $((POWER / DIVIDE))
Explanation:
First line: #!/bin/bash - Shebang specifying Bash interpreter

Second line: echo $((POWER / DIVIDE)) - Uses arithmetic expansion to perform division

How it works:
In arithmetic expansion $(()), variables are referenced by name without $

POWER / DIVIDE performs integer division

The expression 42784 / 32 evaluates to 1337

echo prints the result followed by a newline

Demonstration:
julien@production-503e7013:~$ export POWER=42784
julien@production-503e7013:~$ export DIVIDE=32
julien@production-503e7013:~$ ./9-divide_and_rule | cat -e
1337$
Calculation:
42784 รท 32 = 1337

Key concepts demonstrated:
Arithmetic expansion with $(())

Integer division in shell arithmetic

Variable reference in arithmetic - direct names without $

Environment variables in arithmetic operations

This script will work in your sandbox environment and correctly perform the division using the values from the POWER and DIVIDE environment variables.

